{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_parsifal_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280608658/1957112901/1166.xml":{"full_text":"Joining j&faf\n_ With Sundoy Myning Edition\nPublished by\nTHC EVENING STAR NEWSPAPER COMPANY\nWASHINGTON 4, D. C.\nSomuel H. Kauffmann\nPresident\nRenjamin M. McKtlwoy\nEditor\nMAIN OMICE: IIA St. end denmylvanie Ave. (4)\nNEW YORK: 342 Madison A\u00bba. 117)\nCHICAGO: 221 N. La Salle SI. (1)\nDETROIT; Now C\u00abr*\u00ab*r Building (2)\nSAN FRANCISCO: Russ Building (4)\nIOS ANGELES: 3242 W\u00abs\u00bb Bth St. (3)\nCUROPEAN BUREAU\nPARIS, FRANCE. 21 Buo Do Barri\nDelivered by Carrier\nfvtning and Sundoy Sundoy Evening\nMonthly 1.95 Por Issuo .20 Monthly 1.30\nWookly .45 Wookly 30\nNight Pinal and Sundoy 2.00 Night Finol 0n1y... 1.40\nRotes by Moil\u2014Payable in Advance\nAnywhoro in th\u00ab Unitod Statos\nIvoning and Sunday Sunday Evoning\n1 yoor 28.00 1 yoar 12.00 1 yoar 18 00\n4 months 14.50 6 months 4.50 6 months 9.23\n3 months 7.50 3 months 3.30 3 months 4.73\n1 month 2.60 1 month 1.30 1 month 2.00\nT'lophono: STorling 3-3000\nEntortd ot th\u00ab Post Offict, Washington, D. C.\nos second doss moil matter\nMember of the Associated Press\nThe A'\u00abocinted Press is entitled exclusively to the use for\nrepublication of oil the local news printed in this newspaper\nos well ns A. P. news dispatches.\nA-14\nFRIDAY, NOVEMBER 29, 1957\nIf Unable to Serve\nPresident Eisenhower\u2019s participation\nIn a Thanksgiving Day church service is\nrather conclusive evidence that he is\nmaking a quick recovery from the minor\nstroke he suffered on Monday. This\nprogress is consistent with the expecta\ntions voiced by his doctors and with the\nInformation which has come out of the\nWhite House. We hope that the Presi\ndent will not push himself too hard or\ntoo rapidly. But we welcome the evi\ndence that he is getting well, and we are\nsure that every American shares this\nsentiment.\nIt now is a reasonable Inference\nthat the country will not be faced in the\nImmediate future with the difficult\nquestion of what to do if a President\nshould become unable to discharge the\npowers and duties of his office.\nThe Constitution says that in such\nevent these powers shall devolve on the\nVice President, and that Congress may\nby law make the necessary provision to\nthis end. But the Constitution does not\nsay how or by whom presidential dis\nability is to be determined. Neither\ndoes it spell out specifically what the\nVice President\u2019s status would be, nor\nhow the President would reclaim his\noffice upon recovering from a temporary\ndisability.\nVarious proposals to rectify this\nconstitutional ambiguity have bpen\nmade in the past, but Congress has\nshown little inclination to deal with\nthem. Four measures have been sched\nuled for House consideration early next\nyear, however, and we think that the\nincoming Congress should face up to\nthe issue.\nThere will be a reluctance to do this\nif Mr. Eisenhower's recovery proceeds\nfclong the indicated lines. There is a\nsuggestion of indelicacy, perhaps, in\nmaking provision for a successor to the\npresidency when the President seems\nto be in good health. But Mr. Eisen\nhower did not hesitate to come to grips\nwith the problem last March, when he\nput forward his own suggestions as to\nhow the problem should be dealt with.\nCertainly, now that he has had this mild\nocclusion, Congress should not shrink\nfrom the task.\nWhen the Constitution was drafted\nIts authors did not think of the presi\ndency as an especially powerful office.\nBut over the years it has become so\u2014\nprobably the most powerful and most\nImportant in the world. It is easy to\nthink of situations in which the inability\nof the President to act, even for a day,\nmight have calamitous consequences. In\nawareness of this danger, we do not\nthink it amiss, even while rejoicing in\nMr. Eisenhower's excellent recovery, to\nurge that Congress provide against the\nday on which a stricken President might\nbe unable to rally so quickly from his\nillness.\nGetting Together\nThe impact of the new Federal Aid\nHighway Act of 1956 is being felt by\nmany cities and towns throughout the\ncountry. Unfortunately, few of these\ncommunities have adequate plans for\ntaking advantage of the new highways.\nYet the trend of metropolitan develop\nment is certain to be strongly influenced\nby the opening of the Interstate\nexpressways.\nIt is essential, therefore, that the\nhighway builders and the city planners\nshould get together in a mutual effort\nto lay out routes and approaches best\nsuited to the needs both of the munici\npalities and the interstate system. An\nencouraging move toward this end\nalready has been made in Maryland. At\na recent conference in Baltimore, Fed\neral. State and city officials agreed that\nteamwork is necessary to integrate\nFederal, State and local highways prop\nerly. Similar co-ordination will have\nto be worked out across the country if\nmisunderstandings and mistakes are to\nbe avoided in the planning of the great\nlimited-access highway network.\nFall Guys of the Year\nIt is entirely possible that there Is\nIn the making a more understanding at\ntitude toward sports officials on the part\nof sports writers.\nThis off-season phenomenon grows\nout of the circumstance that the sports\nwriters are making decisions at this time\nof the year, Instead of merely recording\nthem.\nWith time hanging heavier on their\nhands, they are free (\u2019\u2019freer\" is the tact\nful word) to make such momentous de\ncisions as the player of the year in base\nball, the horse of the year, and, of course,\nthe weekly ranking of the Nation\u2019s top\nfootball teams. The honors they award\nin these judgments are frequently noth\ning as compared with the disdain they\nbring upon themselves. 1\nThere was, for instance, the deci\nsion that Mickey Mantle of the Yankees\nwas the baseball player of the year.\nEveryone else knew that actually the\nplayer of the year was Ted Williams or\nRoy Sievers. Next came the choice of\nBold Ruler as 1957\u2019s most significant\nhorse, only to have the selection greeted\nwith jeers by the multitude of wiser lay\nmen who could not see Bold Ruler for\nGallant Man\u2019s dust.\nIn football, a weirdly formless year\nIn which no team has been safe, except\nAuburn which plays safe, the sports\nwriters have had an endlessly wretched\ntime. The one nonneurotic who has sur\nvived it is the man who keeps voting\nweek after week for Elon as the coun\ntry\u2019s top football team. Obviously, the\nElon enthusiast just doesn\u2019t give a hoot\n\u2014which might be a very good idea.\nThe Troops Depart\nBarring unexpected trouble, the last\nof the Federal troops will have left\nLittle Rock when school resumes on\nMonday, and a relatively small contin\ngent of federalized National Guardsmen\nwill take over the policing job.\nThis is something of a happy ending\nto a thoroughly deplorable episode. The\nparatroopers, 1,000 of them, were ordered\nto Little Rock on September 24 by the\nPresident after mob action had forced\nthe removal of nine Negroes from\nCentral High School. This show of\nFederal force, underscored by fixed\nbayonets and clubbed rifles, dispersed\nthe mob and made possible a relatively\nnormal operation of the school on an\nintegrated basis.\nWhat happens now is anyone\u2019s\nguess. As recently as November 17, Gov\nernor Faubus said the only real solution\nwas for the Negro students to withdraw\nfrom the school. But experience in\nother communities where public senti\nment is not unyieldingly against some\nintegration argues otherwise. In Clinton,\nTennessee, for example, integration\nseems to be proceeding smoothly after\nserious initial disorder. There is consid\nerable reason to believe that the same\npattern will show itself in Little Rock.\nThere is at least as much reason to\nbelieve, howeve/-, that this is not true of\nmany Southern communities\u2014commu\nnities in which integration that is forced\nand premature will serve only to destroy\nthe public school system.\nCommon Compulsion\nThe troubles now besetting the\nNorth Atlantic Treaty Organization,\nparticularly between France on one\nhand and Britain and the United States\non the other, have always been inherent\nin all sorts of alliances. Personalities\nhave little to do with the matter, for\nwhenever rifts or quarrels occur in any\ncoalition they occur primarily because\nof a real or fancied clash between the\nseparate national interests and the\ncommon interests of the coalition\u2019s\nmembers.\nIn the case of NATO, for example,\nthe Anglo-French-Amerlcan stresses\nand strains have not been caused by\nSecretary Dulles\u2019 alleged bumbling or\nby British Prime Minister Macmillan\u2019s\nfailure, on his latest visit to Paris, to\nwin the heart of Premier Gaillard and\nsettle all differences with him. The\nsituation involves considerations much\ndeeper than that. For the rift, such as\nit is, has been brought about not by\nanybody\u2019s personality, or lack of it, but\nby a number of basic policy disagree\nments, including especially the dispute\nover military shipments to Tunisia.\nThis dispute revolves around the\nAnglo-American decision to send small\nquantities of arms to President Bour\nguiba\u2019s pro-Western government in\nTunis. The French have reacted bit\nterly. As they see it, the decision con\nstitutes an affront to them by their\ntwo chief allies, and they profess to\nfear that it will be harmful to their,\nvital interests in Algeria, politically,\npsychologically, militarily and other\nwise. But by the same token, having\nin mind the vital interests of the entire\nAtlantic alliance, including their own\nvital interests and those of France as\nwell, Britain and the United States have\nfelt impelled to respond affirmatively\nto Tunisia\u2019s request lest Tunisia turn\nto the Soviet bloc for the weapons it\nwants\u2014a development that would make\nit easier for the Kremlin to spread Us\ndominance-seeking influence farther\nwestward through North Africa.\nThe Anglo-French-American dif\nferences, of course, are not the only\nones that agitate NATO. A comparable\ndispute is the Cyprus issue that divides\nGreece and Britain and Turkey. And\nthere are other actual and potential\nrifts within the alliance. They are rifts\nof varying degrees of seriousness, all\ninvolving conflicting national interests.\nThis is trouble of a kind that a coali\ntion\u2014particularly when it embraces a\nwide variety of countries, including\nformer enemies\u2014can hardly hope to\navoid. In that sense, therefore, the\nAtlantic community\u2019s difficulties are not\nreally surprising: nor are they so great\nthat they cannot be surmounted before\nthey lead to a dangerous deterioration\nor breakup.\nIn any event, NATO\u2019s members all\nbelong to one family\u2014the family of free\nnations\u2014and although some of them\nare sharply at odds over internal issues,\nthey still share a great and over-rid\ning common compulsion to hold fast\ntogether against the external Soviet\nthreat. Everything they cherish depends\nupon their doing that. Quarrel as they\nmay among themselves, this is a fact\nthat they agree upon, and because they\ndo agree upon It, there is ample reason\nto hope and believe that they will act\naccordingly, in unison, to keep on living\nIn freedom.\n-33p**\nI\nl -Up| I\nTime to Start Washing the Dishes\nLETTERS TO THE STAR\nLand 'Squeeze'\nFor five years now. resi\ndents of the \u201cSouthwest\nRedevelopment\u2019\u2019 area have\nbeen victims of mass confu\nsion and poor planning.\nT have been negotiating\nwith the Redevelopment Land\nAgency in an attempt to sell\nmy property. I am told to\neither take their price\u2014\nwhich I consider unfair\u2014or\nwait until they are ready for\nmy area. But I can\u2019t get\nthem to fix the year, much\nless the month, when they\nwill get to my area. This\nprogram has had more \"stop\nend go\u2019\u2019 than the F street\ncar line.\nLike many of my friends in\nthis area. I find myself torn\nbetween two very compelling\ndesires: To sell my property\nand leave this ever-deterior\nating mess, or to hold my\nground and seek the justice\nthat is guaranteed me by law.\nJustice is fine, but what is\nits price and how long will\nit be coming?\nAs a direct result of this\n\u201cgreat adventure in progress,\u201d\nresidents of this area are re\nquired to endure greater and\ngreater hardships with every\npassing day. Blocks of aban\ndoned houses serve only as\nhavens for vagrants and as a\nbreeding ground for an end\nless army of rats. The only\nCatholic school as well as\nseveral public schools have\nbeen or are about to be torn\ndown. Stores and shops are\nclosing by the score. I have\nnoticed with great dismay\nthat many cifcr health and\nsafety regulations exclude the\nSouthwest. As if all of this\nw ere not enough, I am nightly\nlulled to sleep by a pile driver\nplaying its song until mid\nnight. The land agency\nknows, as well as I, that it\ntakes more than four walls\nto make a home. While they\nare not ready to take the\nwalls, they are destroying\neverything in the area that\nmakes them a home. This\n\"squeeze-out\u201d makes their\nprice look better to me every\nday.\nWhile I feel my complaints\nare just, how much can my\nfamily and I endure to see\nthem aired in the courts?\nDuring recent few weeks the\nland agency has pointed with\npride to their record of set\ntling over 80 per cent of their\ncases \u201cout of court.\" How\nmany of these people were\ntruly satisfied and how many\nfound they could no longer\nendure the \"squeeze\"? In the\neyes of many people, the\n\"clean-up\" may represent\n\"social progress.\u201d but to many\nof us it means only endless\nproblems and financial re\ngression. A great deal of\nplanning and study has gone\ninto the \"before and after\" of\nthis operation, but little if\nany has been directed at the\n\"during.\" Victim of Progress.\nIrksome Items\nTwo items in The Star of\nNovember 19 seem capsule\ncomments on one of the un\nlovelier aspects of the spirit\nof our times.\nFirst, there is the interview\nwith actress Julie Harris on\nnatural childbirth. This re\nmark of hers startles: If it\nweren\u2019t for her acting com\nmitments. she said, \u201cI\u2019d like\nto have a child every year.\u201d\nWhat admirable condescen\nsion\u2014God's creative act\nplaced only second after the\nattractions of man-made\nmake-believe!\nMiss Harris, of course, can\nnot be criticized alone. Her\nattitude is all too typical,\nhut none the less deplorable.\nFamilies and children are\nfashionable. It is true\u2014but\nonly on our own terms, sub\nject to human \"planning.\u201d\nMay He forgive our arro\ngance.\nThe second item was \"Birth\nControl Fiat Becoming Top\nIssue.\u201d Tins deals with a\nmore serious matter: The\nprospect of our God-given\nfreedom to propagate, and to\nobey God's laws in this re\ngard. being legislated away\nby unbelievers for whom the\nmoral aspect of \"the popula\ntion problem\" does not exist.\nThey wave the question of\nright and wrong aside, pro\ntesting that economic pres\nsures make it irrelevant May\nI suggest a parallel between\nPen names may be used it\nletters carry writers' correct\nnames and addresses. AU\nletters are subject to conden\nsation.\nthis thinking and some ad\nvanced in the 1850 s and 1860 s\nthat slavery, however im\nmoral. could not be abolished\nbecause it was an economic\nnecessity? We have seen that\nit was not. Let us cope with\n\u201cthe population problem\u201d\nwith all our scientific re\nsources, and also with prayer,\nconfident that there is a so\nlution short of a great mass\noffense against God.\nJulia B. Lowell.\n'Crying for Reform'\nYour November 25 editorial.\n\"Crying for Reform.\u201d points\nto something wrong in our\neducational system.\nIn Russia, unless you are\ncompletely illiterate, if you\ncan pronounce a word you can\nautomatically spell it, since\nRussian has phonetic spel\nling. Russian children don't\nhave to use up mental energy\nstudying how to spell: they\nare not afflicted with the Ir\nrationality of English spelling.\nThe Russians teach chil\ndren that mathematics is fun.\nThey have cut out most of the\nboring calculation exercises\nthat make so many children\nunhappy. Instead they start\nteaching at an early age how\nto think in terms of abstract\nmathematics.\nThis was known long before\nthe Sputnik launchings. For\nexample, in April, 1956, the\nSwedes announced they were\nsending a team of experts to\nmake on-the-spot studies of\nSoviet methods of training\nscientists and engineers. We,\non the other hand, overly\nfrightened at the Russians\nspying on us. have neglected\nour opportunities to spy on\nthe Russians. Thousands of\nSoviet scientific reports are\ncollecting dust on Library of\nCongress shelves for lack of\na program to translate them.\nIt\u2019s time we started using\nour heads. We should cut\nout the emphasis on the kind\nof rote memory which helps\nwin prizes on quiz programs,\nbut contributes little to think\ning ability. Walking ency\nclopedias or good spellers\n'including spellbinders) are\nno substitute for critical and\ncreative minds.\nWhile we have plenty to\nlearn from the Russians, we\nshould also keep our heads\nand not get excessively\ngloomy in comparing our\nselves with them. We can\nstill beat them when it comes\nto the quality of our scientists.\nMaj. Gen. Yaacov Dori,\npresident of Technion. Israel's\nInstitute of Technology, has\nhad a good chance to observe\nboth American and Soviet\nscientists. He said last week\nthat Israel was fashioning\nher technical and scientific\ntraining according to that of\nthe United States rather than\nof Russia. He praises Soviet\nscientists but adds that \"be\ncause of their narrow con\ncepts they are lost outside\ntheir own spheres of opera\ntion due to the peculiar\ntraining of the Soviets, which\nseverely limits horizons and\nproduces a highly efficient\nbut constricted scientist.\u201d\nI am still betting on free\ndom against totalitarianism\nin science and education, as\nelsewhere. When freedom is\nsmug and self-satisfied it is\nat a disadvantage, but when\naroused by moral purpose it\ncan be unbeatable.\nSidney Koretz.\nInteresting\nThe article on the John H.\nKerr Dam in The Sunday\nStar was most interesting to\nthe writer, as we were the\ncobuilders of the dam.\nWe thought it might be\ninteresting to your readers,\nas well as The Star itself\n'for whom we are build\ning The Star's magnifi\ncent new plant), to know\nthat the Chas. H. Tompkins\nCo. of Washington, D. C.,\ntogether with the J. A. Jones\nConstruction Co. of Char\nlotte. N. C., were the co\nbullders of the John H. Kerr\nDam\nFrancis M. Tompkins.\nSenior Vice President. Chas.\nH. Tompkins Co.\nAlerts White House\nAs difficult as it must be\nfor the citizens of this coun\ntry, brainwashed as we are,\nto assimilate the true facts\nof life as presented by the\nrecent Soviet challenge, yet\nit might well be taken for\ngranted that the White\nHouse would take the lead in\nre-educating us and would\nshow the strength and lead\nership so desperately needed.\nAs usual, however, democracy\nlags behind. Business is ap\nparently going on as usual.\nThere are voices, of course,\nwho are urging that the\nAmerican public be prepared\nimmediately for the sacrifices\nwhich must be made if we\nare to accept the challenge\nof the Soviets and get our\nhouse in order. This house\nmust be more up-to-date de\nfense-wise. This house will\nhave fewer luxuries, less but\nter, more guns and more\nbooks.\nI should like to add my\nvoice to those who are plead\ning that the enormous res\nervoir of energy and good\nwill which exists in this\ncountry be not wasted. It is\nquite likely that if the White\nHouse does not raise itself up\nby the bootstraps and go in\nto careful action, it might\nwell be raised from its state\nof lethargy and carelessness\nby another force, and we do\nnot necessarily mean the\nelectorate.\nDorothy Faxon.\nCrime Cases\nIn my twenty-eight years\nin Washington I find it diffi\ncult to express my complete\ngratitude and appreciation to\nthe Metropolitan Police De\npartment and its very capable\nchief. Robert V. Murray.\nBut how. even with a very\nefficient Police Department,\ncan we have a decent city\nwith District coons hamper\ning police in their efforts to\nbring serious crime to an end?\nI refer to the narcotics and\nrape cases thrown out of\ncourt despite sufficient evi\ndence, competent witnesses\nand backed up by highly de\npendable policemen who in a\ngreat many cases risked their\nlives making the cases.\nI call upon The Star to con\ntinue to enlighten its readers\non such miscarriage of jus\ntice.\nJ. Rock Armstrong.\nMideast Unrest\nAt the time when our Gov\nernment is striving to wake\nup the people of the Middle\nEast to the Communist dan\nger, the kind of Arab propa\nganda voiced by Professor\nHitti at the Princeton Club\nhere serves to retard that ef\nfort and help the Kremlin.\nProfessor Hitti apparently\nwants Israel to change from\na modern, progressive, demo\ncratic country to a semifeu\ndal dictator-ridden kind of\nslave state on the Arab pat\ntern when he advocates its\ntransformation into another\nLevantine state.\nFortunately Arab black\nmail threats to join the Com\nmunists if we don\u2019t give them\nwhat they want will get short\nshrift from President Eisen\nhower. The United States is\nnot likely to act against Its\nown interests by weakening\nIsrael.\nIsrael and Turkey are our\ntwo strongest allies in the\nMiddle East. This is acknowl\nedged even by the Cairo news\npaper Ash-Shab, which said\nthat \"Israel is the best ally of\nUnited States policy in the\nMiddle East\nProfessor Hitti should know\nthat our country is ready to\nstrengthen any nation that\nstands with the free world.\nWe cannot, however, allow\nthe Arab war against Israel\nto go on in this present criti\ncal time, and nations which\npersist in this self-destructive\npath cannot expect our favor.\nNor should we give any large\nscale economic aid to coun\ntries which are willing to play\nthe Communist game and ac\nquire arms from the Soviet\nUnion. The time has come\nwhen we must know which of\nthe Middle East countries we\ncan count on and which de\nserve our help. can no\nlonger temporize with Arab\nneutralism. 8. Hauser.\nA\nVISTAS IN SCIENCE\nBy THOMAS R. HENRY\nRussia Tries Farming in Far North\nRussia, with the develop\nment of new scientific meth\nods, is pushing agriculture\nhundreds of miles northward.\nSuccessful culture of fruit\nand cereals is being ac\ncomplished in the Soviet\nUnion\u2019s immense Arctic zone,\nwhich extends for nearly\n7,500 miles from the Kola\nPeninsula, close to Norway\nin the east, to the Chukot\nsky Peninsula across from\nAlaska. In winter it is a\nland of perpetual darkness.\nIn summer vast stretches of\ntundra are covered. with\nflowers and dotted with hun\ndreds of small lakes.\nSuccess of Russian pioneers\nin cultivating this area is\nreported by the Scientific\nand Cultural Organization of\nthe United Nations. Only a\nfew years ago agriculture\nwas considered Impossible in\nthe far north because the\ntopsoil remains frozen\nthrough much of the year.\nDifficulties facing the agri\ncultural pioneers have been\ntremendous, the United Na\ntions report points out. Be\nsides the frozen topsoil they\nhad to contend with swamps,\nlichens and erratic boulders.\nThe conquest was accom\nplished by a small army of\nscientists, engineers and\ntechnicians. They made\nstudies of ihe soil, drained\nswamps and marshlands and\nexperimented with species\nof plants which would grow\nin cold climated. A whole\nnew technology of Arctic\nagriculture has resulted.\nSoil Specially Treated\nBefore planting seeds in\nthe Arctic regions the soil\nmust be specially treated. In\nspring the earth is broken up\nwith disks and then plowed\nto a depth of about four\ninches. Fertilizers are add\ned. After this the earth is\nbroken up again\u2014by mid\nsummer a second plowing is\npossible\u2014this time to a depth\nof about seven inches. This\nis followed by another ses\nsion with the disk plow.\nThe ground processed in this\n;way is planted the following\nspring.\nTo improve the structure\nof the soil a principle of crop\nrotation hat been adopted.\nCereals, vegetables and\ngrasses, especially local va\nrities of clover, are grown in\nturn. Cereals and fruit trees\nare confined largely to the\nsouthernmost parts of the\nArctic zone. Northward, more\npotatoes and vegetables are\ncultivated. Around the town\nTHIS AND THAT\nBy CHARLES F. TRACEWELL\n\"ARLINGTON. Va.\n\"Dear Sir:\n\"We live in a fairly open\nnew suburban development.\n\"How can we go about at\ntracting birds for winter\nfeeding?\n\"Could some sort of feed\ning tray be attached outside\nmy 4-year-old\u2019s bedroom\nwindow, or would most spe\ncies be afraid to come that\nclose to the house?\n\"There are no large trees\nin our block, but the houses\nare fairly far apart. We\u2019ll\nbe looking for your com\nments in your thoroughly\nenjoyable column.\n\u201cYours truly, J. P. B.\u201d\n\nThe birds would not be\nafraid to come close to the\nhouse, but sometimes are\nskittish at the movement of\na human watcher behind the\npane.\nTherefore, it is a good idea,\nand especially after first\nestablishing a feeding sta\ntion in such a position, to\ncurtain the window well, so\nthat movement Inside will\nnot be noticed.\nIn this way. both bird*\nand humans share in the\nfun, and little persons in\nparticular will come to love\nthe birds.\nA feeding tray on a pole\nis best, and we hope those\nwho start one now will not\nbe too upset by other visitors,\nsuch as squirrels, and maybe\nat some time an.opossum!\nThese, too. are hungry in\nthe cold.\nWe have always thought\nthat one of the best lessons\nanyone can learn from a\nbird feeding place is not so\nmuch about birds as about\none's self.\nTo grow red in the face,\nand angry because another\nhungry thing comes to a \u201cfree\nlunch\u201d is .to be highly\nillogical.\nLet us admit that life is\nnot always logical, but still\nit makes little sense to put out\nfood and then try to be selec\ntive about those who come to\neat It.\n\nIn setting up a new Rtation\nclose to the window, the\ncurtains or Venetian blinds\ncan be so arranged that a\nnormal amount of movement\nbehind the pane will not be\nnoticed by those outside.\nIn this way there will be\nnothing to frighten the timid\neaters.\nThe point is that it takes\nonly one frightened bird to\nset all the rest winging away.\nQUESTIONS AND ANSWERS\nBy THE HASKIN SERVICE\nA rF*<irr ran ft an antwri t>t mail tn ant factual question nt writing\nThf livfnintr Star Information Bureau. r\u201e\u2019<\u00bbo tve street NW. Wasniuttor 6*\nD C Pi-a.-e inclose ;i cents for return nostaae\nQ Which of our States has\nthe most important deposits\nof chalk?\u2014R. F.\nA. Kansas claims to be the\nChalk State.\u201d and probably\nhas the country's most fa\nmous deposits of chalk 'cal\ncium carbonate). The Kan\nsas beds are known to scien\ntists tjiroughout the world\nbecause of the rare fossils\nwhich they contain. There\nof Khanfy-Mansysk. on the\nRiver Ob at a somewhat\nhigher latitude than Lenin\ngrad. potatoes and other veg\netables account for a fourth\nof all the crops. Farther\nnorth, in the Komi autono\nmous republic, they make up\n44 per cent. In the Yamalo\nand TaimU* sk i districts*\nwhich border on the> Arctic\ncoastline, the proportion is\n64 per cent, rising to 80 per\ncent on peninsulas extending\ninto the Arctic.\nHorticulturists w-orking in\nthe far north have experi\nmented with several local va\nrieties of apples that with\nstand severe cold. One. a\ntype of rennet, yields very\nsmall fruit. There are sev\neral creeping varieties which\nalmost might be called anple\nvines, however, which produce\nconsiderable crops of fairly\nlarge apples. Even cherry\ntrees have been developed\nwhich flourish out-of-doors\non the Kola Peninsula.\nDuring the past 10 years\ncereals have been pushed far\nther and farther north. Re\ncently Russian scientists de\nveloped two new varieties of\nearly wheat, both of which\ncan be grown in the forest\nareas and tundras of the Arc\ntic zone. Varieties of barley\nand oats, developed by the\nPolar Experimental Station\nof the Soviet Institute of\nAgriculture, now are wide\nspread in the Arctic regions.\n.Some Other Results\nOther cereals are grown for\ncattle fodder. Cultivation of\nmaize, harvested green for\nfodder, has shown very prom\nising initial yields. Potatoes\nand green vegetables are pro\nduced on a large scale. The\nformer, especially, show bet\nter yields than are obtained\nfar to the southward.\nRemarkable results have\nbeen achieved with vegetables\nusually associated with much\nwarmer climates, such as to\nmatoes. cauliflowers and on\nions. Special protection nat\nurally is necessary against\nthe icy winds. Fields, kitch\nen gardens and orchards are\nscreened by trees, hedges or\nsnow shields.\nAt present, according to\nthe Unesco report, there are\nmore than 200 large state\nfarms in the Arctic zone, to\ngether with several thousand\nsmaller farms. More than a\nhalf-million acres are under\ncultivation, especially in the\nneighborhood of new indus\ntrial and mining cities which\nhave no other easy sources\nof supply.\nThis is nature's basic de\nfense in birdland.\nWe have watched a band\nof common sparrows be\nchanged in a second from\na peacefully eating group to\nan instant commotion of\nfeathers, Just because one\nbird in the group had spotted\na hawk.\nBy this one bird's ready\nfear and action, both It and\nall its comrades are saved the\npossibility of attack for the\ntime being.\nIn this way nature takes\neare of her own, at least to\na certain limited sense.\n\nIn establishing a new feed\ning station, one must be pre\npared for no birds to come\nfor quite a long time, varying\naccording to unknown factors.\nOne can never be sure of\nJust why birds will not come\nwhen food is first put out for\nthem.\nIt may be a circling hawk,\nfar in the sky.\nIt might be a belligerent\nmockingbird, playing dog in\nthe manger.\nIt might even be the color\nof the feeding station itself.\nA dead white, for instance,\nis not fancied by birds.\nWe have had them stay\naway from a feeder because\nwe put out cottage cheese to\nsee if they would eat it.\nThey would not; what is\nmore, they wouldn\u2019t even\ncome to the place at all, but\ntreated it, one and all. as if\nit contained some sort of\nsubtle avian poison.\n\nTherefore, do not give up\nhope if the birds do not in\nstantly start patronizing a\nnew eating place.\nEven as in human eateries,\ncustom must be built up.\nDo the best you can, and\ndo not worry too much about\nit.\nIn.time, everything will be\nall right.\nThe less human activity\noutside near the station, the\nbetter, naturally enough.\nBuds are timid, properly so\nfor their own safety. They\nwill seldom act Just as you\nmight wish them to act.\nBut if care is taken, with\na dose of patience, and good\nfood, in time they will come,\nsimply because they are hun\ngry and you supply their\nneed.\nProperly protected seed,\ngrains and suet will last a\nlong time, and will be good\nenough to eat, even if the\nbirds do not come for some\ndays.\nare great beds of chalk in\na number of States\u2014Texas,\nArkansas and Montana\namong them.\nQ. What kind of chicken\nis a caponette? M. T.\nA The name is applied to\nchickens which have been\ntreated with hormones <dl\nethylstilbestrol) to make\nthem plump and tender.","height":"28680","width":"17961"}}
